<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,402,1258]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,559,510,538]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Description of 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[389,405,510,524]" fontSize="6" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">rd</superScript>
instar larva.
</emphasis>
Size: BL 
<quantity box="[673,777,513,538]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="8.5">8.50 mm</quantity>
; HL 
<quantity box="[833,936,513,538]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="2.05">2.05 mm</quantity>
, HW 
<quantity box="[1002,1105,513,538]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.85" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="1.85">1.85 mm</quantity>
, ML 
<quantity box="[1166,1269,513,538]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.66" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="1.66">1.66 mm</quantity>
, HW/HL 0.90, ML/HL 0.81. General colouring dark brown, dotted with small paler markings and a median light brown stripe running on the dorsal side, ventral side paler, mottled with dark brown; head capsule dark brown with darker areas on the sides, ventral side dark brown with a pair of darker markings at the base of the mandibles (
<figureCitation box="[1237,1316,621,646]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="19.[151,249,1964,1986]" captionTargetBox="[242,1298,238,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-44@19.[230,1356,193,1940]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 9. Nemoleon notatus (Rambur, 1842), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero, Capo Caccia). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–i: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909393/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 9f</figureCitation>
); antennae black; mandibles dark brown, internal margin paler; legs pale; setae of the body mainly black, interspersed with shorter white ones. Head slightly longer than wide; dorsal side covered by whitish scale-like setae (
<figureCitation box="[1334,1422,693,718]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="19.[151,249,1964,1986]" captionTargetBox="[242,1298,238,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-44@19.[230,1356,193,1940]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 9. Nemoleon notatus (Rambur, 1842), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero, Capo Caccia). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–i: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909393/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 9b</figureCitation>
); anterior margin of the labrum covered by white dolichasters (
<figureCitation box="[845,929,729,754]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="19.[151,249,1964,1986]" captionTargetBox="[242,1298,238,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-44@19.[230,1356,193,1940]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 9. Nemoleon notatus (Rambur, 1842), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero, Capo Caccia). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–i: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909393/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 9d</figureCitation>
); mandibles bent upward (
<figureCitation box="[1231,1308,729,754]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="19.[151,249,1964,1986]" captionTargetBox="[242,1298,238,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-44@19.[230,1356,193,1940]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 9. Nemoleon notatus (Rambur, 1842), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero, Capo Caccia). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–i: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909393/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 9i</figureCitation>
), relatively robust, shorter than the head capsule (
<figureCitation box="[586,670,765,790]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="19.[151,249,1964,1986]" captionTargetBox="[242,1298,238,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-44@19.[230,1356,193,1940]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 9. Nemoleon notatus (Rambur, 1842), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero, Capo Caccia). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–i: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909393/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 9a</figureCitation>
); interdental mandibular setae whitish: (3–4)(1)(1)(0); sparse black setae are disposed on the external margin of the mandible; labial palpi covered by white dolichasters (
<figureCitation box="[1336,1423,801,826]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="19.[151,249,1964,1986]" captionTargetBox="[242,1298,238,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-44@19.[230,1356,193,1940]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 9. Nemoleon notatus (Rambur, 1842), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero, Capo Caccia). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–i: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909393/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1392,1423,801,826]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="9.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="g" value="9.0">9g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
). Pronotum covered by white scale-like setae (
<figureCitation box="[650,736,837,862]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1936,1958]" captionTargetBox="[241,1323,508,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-216@11.[233,1335,499,1910]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 4. Pronotum of 3rd instar larvae of Dendroleontini and Nemoleontini; A, Dendroleon pantherinus; B, Nemoleon notatus; C, Distoleon tetragrammicus; D, Creoleon lugdunensis; E, Neuroleon nemausiensis; F, Macronemurus appendiculatus; G, Megistopus lucasi; H, Gymnocnemia variegata. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909373" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909373/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[748,777,837,862]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="19.[151,249,1964,1986]" captionTargetBox="[242,1298,238,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-44@19.[230,1356,193,1940]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 9. Nemoleon notatus (Rambur, 1842), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero, Capo Caccia). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–i: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909393/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">9c</figureCitation>
); first pair of mesothoracic setiferous processes white (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="19.[151,249,1964,1986]" captionTargetBox="[242,1298,238,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-44@19.[230,1356,193,1940]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 9. Nemoleon notatus (Rambur, 1842), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero, Capo Caccia). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–i: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909393/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 9e</figureCitation>
). Abdominal spiracles slightly raised; IX abdominal sternite ventrally equipped with a pair of spiniform setae; rastra prominent, bearing 4 digging setae of which the internal seta is the shortest (
<figureCitation box="[1076,1174,909,934]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[151,249,1564,1586]" captionTargetBox="[231,1357,197,1529]" captionTargetId="figure-239@10.[188,1398,193,1584]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. IX and VIII abdominal sternite of 3rd instar larva of Dendroleontini and Nemoleontini. A, Dendroleon pantherinus; B, Nemoleon notatus; C, Distoleon tetragrammicus; D, Creoleon lugdunensis; E, Neuroleon assimilis; F, Macronemurus appendiculatus; G, Megistopus lucasi; H, Gymnocnemia variegata. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909369" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909369/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figs. 3B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1186,1218,909,934]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="19.[151,249,1964,1986]" captionTargetBox="[242,1298,238,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-44@19.[230,1356,193,1940]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 9. Nemoleon notatus (Rambur, 1842), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero, Capo Caccia). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; a–i: diagnostic characters, see species description." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909393/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">9h</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,402,1258]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,343,945,970]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Bio-ecology.</emphasis>
A poorly known species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rambur" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[632,747,946,969]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Nemoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="notatus">
<emphasis box="[632,747,946,969]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">N. notatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is associated with open arid environments such as savannahs, while in Europe this seldom collected antlion is mainly reported from arid coastal sites. In 
<collectingRegion box="[1196,1292,981,1006]" country="Italy" name="Sardegna" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Sardinia</collectingRegion>
, this species lives in arid and rocky scrublands. The only known larva was discovered buried under a rock overhang.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,402,1258]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1053,1078]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Distribution.</emphasis>
A widely distributed afrotropical taxon reaching North Africa, the Middle East and southernmost western Europe (
<collectingCountry box="[498,566,1089,1114]" name="Spain" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Spain</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[578,757,1089,1114]" country="Spain" name="Illes Baleares" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Balearic Islands</collectingRegion>
and Sardinia).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,402,1258]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1125,1150]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is the only member of the genus whose larva is known, comprising the only other European congener, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Stein, 1863)" baseAuthorityName="Stein" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[382,722,1161,1186]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Nemoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="poecilopterus">
<emphasis box="[382,568,1161,1186]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">N. poecilopterus</emphasis>
(Stein, 1863)
</taxonomicName>
distributed from south 
<collectingCountry box="[989,1041,1161,1186]" name="Italy" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Italy</collectingCountry>
eastward (
<bibRefCitation author="Stange, L. A." box="[1163,1309,1161,1186]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 565" refId="ref42121" refString="Stange, L. A. (2004) A systematic catalog, bibliography and classification of the world antlions (Insecta: Neuroptera: Myrmeleontidae). Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 74, 1 - 565." type="journal article" year="2004">Stange 2004</bibRefCitation>
). The larva of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rambur" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[181,296,1198,1221]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Nemoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="notatus">
<emphasis box="[181,296,1198,1221]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">N. notatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily recognizable from all the other known European members of the tribe thanks to the peculiar chaetotaxy of the head and pronotum.
</paragraph>
